#X text 266 407 In this example \, for the sake of simplicity \, we have a fixed decay time at 750 ms \, a cutoff frequency at MIDI pitch '50' (D3 \, close to 150hz) and the maximum modulated cutoff is 100 (about 2.6 Khz)., f 44;
#X msg 139 260 norm \$1;
#X obj 139 232 tgl 19 0 empty empty empty 0 -10 0 12 #dfdfdf #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X text 267 276 The [adsr~] could also be used with just the decay parameter \, but this is straight to the point. We still have a proper [adsr~] for the amplitude., f 44;
#X text 218 142 In the last example we had an [adsr~] for the envelope filter \, but we can use a simpler one like a [decay~] object being triggered by impulses. Try normalizing the gate input in order to have a consistent behviour regardless of the gate value., f 50;
#X text 266 340 An [adsr~] could also add a release stage to the filter modulation \, making it sound less brigth when releasing the note. You can do that as an excercise., f 44;
